                <div type="translation">
                    <p>Marcus Scribonius Syneros, in charge of buildings. Hilarus, his freedman,
               made (this).</p>
                </div>
            
        
        
                <div type="commentary">
                    <p>A simple double line border surrounds both fields of the bipartite columbarium slab now broken away at the left side; a single vertical line divides the enclosed campus into two fields. Our inscription preserves the epitaph of the right field and the last letters of what seem to be the only two lines of the epitaph on the left. Above the double-line border, a decorative row of alternating left and right-facing palm fronds connected to each other by wavy lines runs across the top of the tablet; the ends of the wavy lines are punctuated by small holes, perhaps originally holding metal fixtures. A nail hole with the nail in place pierces the stone at the ride side, at the end of line 2 of the text.<p/>
                       <p>Line 1: tall I in the first I in "Scribonius". The last letter of the line is carved outside the campus within the double-line border; the right stroke of the preceiding V intersects the inner line of the two-line border.</p>
                </div>
            
        
        
